1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:35,496
At the end of a factory shift in Orange, New Jersey, young women stepped into the night with luminous dust on their dresses, hair, and skin. They painted watch dials for soldiers using a glowing compound sold as Undark. Their employer said it was safe. The job was patriotic, fashionable, and well paid. But the glow followed them home. It settled inside their bodies and began damaging their bones from within. This is the story of the Radium Girls and the company that transformed a scientific miracle into an occupational death sentence.

2
00:00:35,496 --> 00:01:16,367
Radium was celebrated as a wonder material. Mixed into paint, it made watch faces, compasses, and aircraft instruments visible in darkness without electricity. During the First World War, that capability became valuable to the military. The Radium Luminous Material Corporation, later called the United States Radium Corporation, expanded production in Orange, New Jersey. Hundreds of workers, many of them teenage girls and young women, sat in rows painting tiny numbers by hand. Every finished dial increased output. Every speck of radioactive paint entering the room remained invisible on the company ledger.

3
00:01:16,367 --> 00:01:57,743
The brush tips quickly lost their point. Supervisors taught a faster method: shape the bristles with the lips, dip the brush into luminous paint, then draw the next number. Lip, dip, paint. Repeat it throughout the shift. Every repetition placed radium directly into the mouth. The women asked whether the substance was dangerous and were reassured. Some used the glowing paint on fingernails or teeth. Modern occupational safety guidance still cites these dial painters as an example of internal radiation exposure. A hazardous laboratory material had been converted into an ordinary piece-rate routine.

4
00:01:57,743 --> 00:02:43,031
The warnings appeared first in dentists' offices. Teeth loosened. Gums failed to heal. Jaws became painful and fragile. Grace Fryer had worked at the Orange plant from 1917 to 1920. By 1924, a dentist examining her severe jaw damage suspected a connection to her former job. Other painters developed anemia, fractures, bone damage, and cancers. The body can deposit radium in bone because it behaves somewhat like calcium. Once there, radioactive decay repeatedly exposes nearby tissue. Leaving the factory did not end the danger. The source had become part of the workers' skeletons.

5
00:02:43,031 --> 00:03:25,967
United States Radium challenged the connection between the factory and the illnesses. Some victims faced humiliating alternative explanations for their symptoms. Delay favored the company: occupational disease was difficult to prove, medical knowledge was developing, and legal deadlines could expire while workers searched for answers. In 1925, Essex County medical examiner Harrison Martland published evidence identifying internal radium as the cause of the painters' bone disease and anemia. The science was becoming harder to dismiss. But scientific evidence alone did not create accountability. The women still needed attorneys willing to confront a powerful employer.

6
00:03:25,967 --> 00:04:07,463
Grace Fryer spent years searching for legal help. She eventually joined Katherine Schaub, Quinta McDonald, Albina Larice, and Edna Hussman in a case against United States Radium. By the time hearings began, the women were gravely ill. Postponements made delay a weapon. Newspapers reported on dying workers being asked to wait for justice. In 1928, the case ended in a settlement providing money, annual payments, and medical and legal expenses. No settlement could remove radium from their bones. But their action publicly established that a corporation could be forced to answer for a workplace poison.

7
00:04:07,463 --> 00:04:50,351
The scandal extended beyond New Jersey. In Ottawa, Illinois, the Radium Dial Company continued employing painters. Workers were reassured even as the New Jersey deaths became known. Catherine Donohue and other Illinois women fought a separate legal battle while their health deteriorated. Their cases showed that the danger was not one mysterious local accident. It was embedded in an industry that valued luminous output over honest risk. In 1938, Illinois workers won damages after years of resistance. The name Radium Girls came to represent workers across several cities whose bodies supplied evidence that institutions had failed to act upon.

8
00:04:50,351 --> 00:05:32,471
Radium turned the workers' bodies into permanent records. Researchers measured radiation in living painters and studied remains after death. The element's persistence allowed scientists to connect internal exposure with bone cancer and other injuries over decades. Later studies followed thousands of people employed in the luminizing industry. The evidence changed how medicine understood radioactive materials deposited inside the body. The women never volunteered to become research subjects. Their exposure came from instructions given at work under assurances of safety. Yet their suffering produced knowledge that influenced radiation protection for generations.

9
00:05:32,471 --> 00:06:22,055
The dial painters' cases became landmarks in occupational health. They helped demonstrate that workers harmed by diseases appearing slowly could still challenge an employer. Lip-pointing was abandoned. Exposure controls improved. Radiation protection became more formal. These changes did not come from corporate foresight. Workers, dentists, physicians, journalists, scientists, and attorneys forced the evidence into public view. OSHA still references radium dial painters when explaining ionizing radiation hazards. Their legacy survives in contamination controls, monitoring, protective equipment, and the obligation to tell workers what substances they are handling. Each rule followed a warning that had once been ignored.

10
00:06:22,055 --> 00:07:09,240
The danger outlived the factory. Radioactive waste contaminated former United States Radium properties in New Jersey. The site eventually entered the federal Superfund cleanup system. The company could close, reorganize, or disappear, but radium and contaminated soil remained. This is the accounting pattern behind many industrial disasters: profits are recorded during productive years, while illness, litigation, and cleanup continue across generations. A watch glowed for decades. Radium-226 has a half-life of about sixteen hundred years. Corporate paperwork could end a business. It could not end the radioactive material left in buildings, land, and human bone.

11
00:07:09,240 --> 00:07:55,584
The images are unforgettable: glowing dresses, painted teeth, damaged jaws, and luminous watches. But the underlying pattern is ordinary. A new technology creates excitement. Demand rises faster than regulation. Workers receive reassurance because caution would slow production. Early illnesses are treated as isolated cases. Experts debate while legal clocks run down. Only after victims organize does the invisible cost become public. That pattern did not end with radium. It appears whenever a company knows more about a product's danger than the people exposed to it. The real test begins when evidence threatens the profitable story being sold.

12
00:07:55,584 --> 00:08:34,727
The women were told the glow meant progress. In reality, it was evidence: on their clothing, in their homes, inside their bones, and eventually inside court records and safety standards. Their employer tried to separate the product from the suffering required to make it. The Radium Girls made that separation impossible. They turned private illness into public knowledge. The watches now sit in museums and the factories are closed or cleaned. Their enduring legacy is the principle that workers have a right to know what enters their bodies, and that a corporation cannot make poison disappear by hiding it in the dark.

